  <!-- ── The Legal Foundation ──────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <div class="licensed-break licensed-break--ink">
      <p>
        The skinny union rests on a legal foundation that is sound under existing law and
        does not depend on any court adopting a new rule.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Introduction">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">&nbsp;</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Introduction</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <p>This is where we lay out in some detail the ideas and considerations that have shaped the Skinny Union Project.</p>
<p>Our perspective: We want workers to get paid more.</p>
<p>A lot of workers are underpaid because they are not taking advantage of collective bargaining. Barely 6% of American private sector workers is a union member (5.9% in 2025, per BLS).</p>
<p>But also: bargaining leverage is limited, and any amount of leverage spent on non-pay items reduces leverage for pay and benefits. And yet, traditional unions uniformly devote loads of bargaining power to non-pay items, especially those related to job security: progressive discipline, grievance procedures, arbitrations, minor work rules, union bureaucracy and politics, etc.</p>
<p>That “full fat” union model has served a lot of employees for a long time, but it doesn’t serve everyone, and it should not be the only option.</p>
<p>Somewhere on the menu should be a more targeted solution that offers an easier entry point into the benefits of collective bargaining. We call it the skinny union: it is a union formed to focus the power of collective bargaining solely on pay and benefits. It is simple, it is easy to explain, it doesn’t waste time or leverage on work rules and grievance procedures.</p>
<p>Now, that focus means that the skinny union model is basically leaving the employee handbook unchanged as to working conditions and job security: members would still be at-will employees. We think there are a lot of workers for whom this approach will be attractive: mostly professional workers who want the pay benefits of collective bargaining but who are either hesitant to take on the complexity of the “full fat” union model or who rationally just want a union to get paid more.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="The Problem">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Section I</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">The Problem</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <p>Non-union professional workers are underpaid because of information asymmetry, because of the disadvantage of negotiating alone on one’s own behalf, because of inability to capture market rates for their job, and because the job security risk they take on as at-will employees is not properly priced.</p>
<p>Imagine a new program officer at a large nonprofit with a salary offer. It feels low. Maybe she negotiates for an extra two grand and thinks she has done well. Maybe she pushes for the high end of the advertised salary range and thinks she has done well. She has not done well. And she has no way of knowing how much of the employer’s money she left on the table. The employer has all the information. The employee has, what, GlassDoor?</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
The employer has all the information. The employee has, what, GlassDoor?
</blockquote>
<p>The related problem of course is that she is alone. She is at the table with all her own inhibitions about risk taking, and about the impression she is making about the kind of personality she has. There are downsides to seeming graspy! Heck, there are downsides to <em>feeling</em> graspy! Right or wrong, there is just a limit to what the average person can achieve in separating their own personality from the negotiating table, especially when what they are negotiating for is their own services.</p>
<p>But there is more! For example: an IT worker at a big bank sees a job that is more or less identical to her own posted at a similar firm in a similar location. That job is posted at $15k more than her current salary. But she would not switch jobs for less than $30k more because switching jobs is a huge hassle and also risky. Changing jobs has transaction costs. Rounds of interviews. Lining up references. Worries about culture fit. What if the new firm doesn’t have anyone she wants to wait in line for a taco with? It’s an anxiety inducing thing to change jobs. The employer knows this. The employer is not going to give her that $15k raise that the market is saying she is worth. So it is just lost to her. Long tenured employees are typically disadvantaged by this phenomenon as new employees are brought in at market rates while annual raises fail to keep pace with the market. This sort of salary compression dynamic can be viewed as a premium paid to “job hoppers” or a cost extracted from the long-tenured staff.</p>
<p>And of course there is the job security risk. She is at-will. Her employer does not have to provide a reason for terminating her. It's not that capricious firings are common — employers that fire talented employees capriciously are not usually very successful. It's that the employer retains a wide zone of discretion short of caprice, and that flexibility is worth real money to the employer. Whatever it is worth, it almost certainly has not been priced into her salary.</p>
<p>That’s the world of the at-will, non-unionized professional. It comes with a characteristically American economic dynamism and freedom that generates high profits and (most of the time!) a liquid labor market with plentiful jobs but also (frequently!) precarity and persistent underpayment.</p>
<p>Traditional unions attack that precarity. They impose just cause termination rules, grievance procedures, arbitration mechanisms, and sometimes even minimum staffing levels. But in attacking the precarity, they are spending the limited resource of bargaining leverage that could otherwise be brought to bear on pay. And they are, not incidentally, building out substantial union staff bureaucracy to manage all that. And that build out raises the cost of union dues to support the job security infrastructure (the grievance hearings, the arbitrations, etc).</p>
<p>Meanwhile, something else has been going on in state houses and city halls. The statutory protections against unfair employment practices have been expanding at local levels. The floor is rising. The gap between “full fat” union protections and the baseline law is no longer the gap between Henry Clay Frick and Al Shanker. And employer practices have responded. Ask any management-side employment lawyer: notwithstanding the technical reality of “at will” employment, employers in these jurisdictions are strongly encouraged to base individual employment decisions on performance. So the same complexity, politics and bureaucracy of a traditional union is covering a smaller field of risk – but the unions haven’t slimmed down in response.</p>
<div class="box-break"><aside class="box-statutory-sampler">
  <p class="box-eyebrow">Reference &mdash; what &ldquo;dense statutory protection&rdquo; means in practice</p>

  <p class="box-intro">State and local authorities have been raising the bar of employee protections &mdash; broadening anti-discrimination categories, restricting unfair non-competes and NDAs, strengthening retaliation protections, and more. Three examples:</p>

  <dl class="box-jurisdictions">

<div class="box-entry">
      <dt class="box-juris">New York</dt>
      <dd>
        <p class="box-layer"><span class="box-layer-label">State</span><a href="https://dol.ny.gov/pay-transparency" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pay-range disclosure</a> required in job postings, reaching employers with as few as four employees; salary-history inquiries banned; <a href="https://dhr.ny.gov/protected-characteristics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Human Rights Law</a> covers nineteen protected categories.</p>
        <p class="box-layer"><span class="box-layer-label">New York City</span><a href="https://www.nyc.gov/site/cchr/law/the-law.page" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Human Rights Law</a> extends to more than twenty-five categories, including lawful source of income, caregiver status, height, and weight &mdash; broader than the state list it sits on top of.</p>
      </dd>
    </div>

<div class="box-entry">
      <dt class="box-juris">Colorado</dt>
      <dd>
        <p class="box-layer"><span class="box-layer-label">State</span>The broadest <a href="https://cdle.colorado.gov/dlss/labor-laws-by-topic/equal-pay-for-equal-work-act" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">pay-transparency mandate</a> in the country: every employer with at least one Colorado employee must disclose a pay range, notify all employees of openings the same day a posting goes up, and disclose compensation at each step of a career-progression track. Non-competes void below an earnings threshold, with a statutory penalty running per affected worker.</p>
        <p class="box-layer box-layer-absent">No comparably distinct municipal layer in these categories &mdash; the state framework is the operative one statewide.</p>
      </dd>
    </div>

<div class="box-entry">
      <dt class="box-juris">Washington, D.C.</dt>
      <dd>
        <p class="box-layer"><span class="box-layer-label">District</span>Functions as both state and city. <a href="https://ohr.dc.gov/page/protected-traits" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Human Rights Act</a> reaches twenty-three protected traits &mdash; the widest list in this sample &mdash; including political affiliation, personal appearance, family responsibilities, and homeless status, and extends to independent contractors and unpaid interns. <a href="https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/code/titles/32/chapters/14A" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pay-range disclosure</a> required of employers with a single employee. <a href="https://code.dccouncil.gov/us/dc/council/laws/24-175" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Non-competes void</a> below a statutory threshold just above $150,000, adjusted annually for inflation &mdash; set far higher for certain medical specialists.</p>
      </dd>
    </div>

  </dl>

  <p class="box-caption">Illustrative, not exhaustive &mdash; chosen to show how state and municipal layers combine. Links go to the primary government source for each item. Figures current as of 2026; thresholds and effective dates shift from year to year and should be re-checked before publication.</p>
</aside></div>
<p>The overwhelming dominance of the traditional union model means professional workers perceive a false choice between being basically alone at the bargaining table or signing up for something not that different from the Teamsters. That legacy model only makes sense if workers are so worried about job security and their employer’s control of work rules that they are willing to give up substantial pay and benefits to fix it.</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
The overwhelming dominance of the traditional union model means professional workers perceive a false choice between being basically alone at the bargaining table or signing up for something not that different from the Teamsters.
</blockquote>
<p>Should they be? Maybe some should be, but there are many categories of professional workers – program officers, IT professionals, journalists, higher ed administrators, paralegals, even school teachers – who should be more worried about getting paid more than locking down job security. This is especially true in large cities with liquid labor markets and growing statutory protections.</p>
<p>A skinny union can deliver that. It is a coalition of employees formed for the sole purpose of using their collective bargaining power to maximize wages and benefits. The skinny union directs bargaining power at getting paid for the risk that at-will employees take rather than directing scarce bargaining resources at changing the at will market. No elaborate work rules, no grievance hearings, just better pay. Instead of attacking precarity, the skinny union gets workers paid for it.</p>
<p>Perhaps most importantly, though, the skinny union is a slimmer, easier to communicate, less daunting entry point into the truly powerful tool of collective bargaining that traditional unions have been slow to organize. There is a massive gap between public approval of unions and unionization rates. Could that be because there is no simpler, focused version of unionization? No lower lift entry point? The fact is that “full fat” union model has become so dominant as to be practically exclusive. In a sense, it is the exclusive nature of that model that the Skinny Union Project offers to disrupt.</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
The fact is that “full fat” union model has become so dominant as to be practically exclusive.
</blockquote>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Why Hasn’t This Happened Already?">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Section II</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Why Hasn’t This Happened Already?</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <p>Hard to say, but most likely a combination of workers being uninformed and unions having adverse incentives. Employees may have an incentive to build a skinny union, but do not know how. Traditional labor unions know how, but have no incentives to do so. A skinny union does not support the bureaucratic infrastructure of unions. It runs counter to the traditional union focus on job security rather than just getting everyone paid more.</p>
<p>And it is not surprising that employees have failed to develop this on their own. Labor law is increasingly obscure to the layman – union membership is hovering near post-War lows and fewer and fewer employees have either been a member of a union or even had a close relative in a union. It is increasingly rare for attorneys to know much about labor law. As a result, these employees are not aware that all of the tools necessary to assemble a union that would target the issues they most care about have been available for generations. And not only are they not organically learning about the legal apparatus that would allow them to form a skinny union, nobody has an incentive to build it for them.</p>
<p>Traditional unions have no internal incentive to propose a model that reduces their scope. Union staff is funded by dues, and dues are proportional to membership and the breadth of services the union provides. The grievance function (processing member complaints, representing workers in disciplinary proceedings, pursuing arbitration) is administratively intensive and employs significant staff. A union that bargained over wages and benefits only would be a leaner, cheaper organization. It would also be a smaller organization in terms of staff, revenue, and institutional presence. There is no internal political constituency within the labor movement for voluntary institutional downsizing, even where the resulting model might serve workers better.</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
Traditional unions have no internal incentive to propose a model that reduces their scope.
</blockquote>
<p>The consequence is that the skinny union idea does not get proposed to workers by the institutions workers look to for information about collective organizing. And without a proposal, most workers — especially professional workers with limited experience of labor organizing — do not know that something like this is possible. The skinny union is not a radical departure from existing law; it is a configuration of existing legal tools that no one has packaged and promoted for the specific class of workers who would benefit from it.</p>
<p>But isn’t the absence of any attempt itself evidence that workers don't actually want such a union? Part of the answer is above — nobody with the knowledge has had the incentive, and nobody with the incentive has had the knowledge. Part of it is actually historical: the job security focused, “full fat” union template was locked in by the circumstances of its founding era, not chosen from a menu of alternatives.</p>
<div class="box-break"><aside class="box-history-bundle">
  <p class="box-eyebrow">Historical context &mdash; why wages and the grievance apparatus were ever bundled</p>
  <h3 class="box-title">A bundle assembled by wartime, not by design</h3>

  <p class="box-para">But how did traditional unions get to this place &mdash; where they are expected to trade pay for job security, where they are expected to create and participate in complicated disciplinary procedures and grievance machinery? Not surprisingly, the trade of pay for job security started with a wartime wage freeze.</p>

  <p class="box-para"><a href="https://www.bls.gov/opub/mlr/cwc/compensation-from-world-war-ii-through-the-great-society.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Federal wage controls during the Second World War</a> capped what employers could pay in cash. Unable to compete on salary for scarce labor, employers turned to fringe benefits instead.</p>

  <p class="box-para">Also, in exchange for organized labor&rsquo;s wartime no-strike pledge, the federal government built the <a href="https://www.nationalww2museum.org/war/articles/smith-connally-act-and-labor-battles-home-front" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">National War Labor Board</a> into a body empowered to arbitrate disputes to a binding conclusion. The grievance machinery now standard in American labor contracts consolidated in those same years.</p>

  <p class="box-para">It makes sense, right? Government freezes wages. Labor needs to be compensated with something. Labor gets job security. Unions get hooked on the political benefits of this machinery and it gets entrenched. A few decades later, and most people have forgotten that this trade is even really happening. It&rsquo;s just the water traditional unions swim in. To leave it behind feels strange.</p>

  <p class="box-para">Economic historians document how sharply the wage distribution compressed across this same decade &mdash; Goldin and Margo&rsquo;s <a href="https://academic.oup.com/qje/article-abstract/107/1/1/1925779" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">&ldquo;Great Compression&rdquo;</a> measures the magnitude &mdash; and we cite that record only for the fact of the compression and the era in which these institutions hardened, not as proof of what caused them. Goldin and Margo themselves attribute the compression to several forces, wartime wage policy among them, not to wartime policy alone.</p>
</aside></div>
<p>Meanwhile, overall approval of unions in the United States stands at 68% (Gallup, 2025) — a level last seen in the early 1960s — while union membership stands at 10% of the workforce (and much less than that for the private sector). The gap between approval in concept and actual membership is not explained by ideological hostility to collective bargaining. But, it could be explained by the mismatch between what traditional unions offer (grievance machinery, complicated job rules, dues and politics) and what large categories of workers actually want (better pay!). It could also be because the traditional “full fat” union model is daunting, and no one is offering a simpler, focused entry point into unionization.</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
The gap between approval in concept and actual membership is not explained by ideological hostility to collective bargaining. But, it could be explained by the mismatch between what traditional unions offer (grievance machinery, complicated job rules, dues and politics) and what large categories of workers actually want (better pay!).
</blockquote>
<p>Now, statutes like Wisconsin's Act 10 also have narrowed bargaining to wages, but those were built to shrink what workers could win: scope in that case is restricted by force of law, the wage outcome itself capped, dues machinery stripped, recertification imposed. That is leverage-<em>capping</em>: scope narrowed against workers' choosing, to reduce the outcome. The skinny union is the <em>opposite</em> move wearing a superficially similar silhouette. Nothing is restricted by law; the full economic arsenal stays on the table; <em>the members adopt the focus themselves</em> and can reframe it; and the entire structure exists to maximize the wage outcome. Act 10 took the pay upside away. The skinny union exists for nothing else. Scope limitation <em>imposed</em> in order to shrink worker power and scope limitation <em>chosen</em> to concentrate it are not the same act, and the difference shows in every operative detail.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Legal Framework Today">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Section III</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Legal Framework Today</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <p>A skinny union is eminently doable under the law today. The right to form a union is of course well settled and protected by federal law. The question for the skinny union is how to go about achieving the focus and simplicity that it aims for. Federal law requires a recognized union to bargain in good faith over all “mandatory” subjects when they are raised, and there are quite a few of these under the heading of “terms and conditions of employment” set out in Section 8(d) of the National Labor Relations Act — discipline, scheduling, and the like — so a union cannot simply refuse to deal with non-pay items. So it might seem like the law actually requires the “full fat” union model.</p>
<p>Skinny unions work under existing law not by eliminating non-pay items from their remit, but by not bargaining <em>changes</em> to those items. In other words, the skinny union is formed in a company that already has practices and maybe policies related to all the non-pay items. In most places there is an employee handbook that covers these items, including important ones like at-will employment. What the skinny union can do is bargain with a goal of using its leverage solely on improving pay and benefits while declining to extract changes to any non-pay items.</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
Skinny unions work under existing law not by eliminating non-pay items from their remit, but by not bargaining changes to those items.
</blockquote>
<p>More specifically: under <em>H.K. Porter Co. v. NLRB</em> (1970), the National Labor Relations Board cannot compel either party to agree to any particular term; the statute protects the parties' freedom to settle on whatever terms good-faith bargaining produces, including the outcome that an existing arrangement on non-pay items stays exactly as it is. A valid agreement has never been required to contain new terms on every mandatory subject. Discharging the duty on the non-pay subjects is, in itself, easy.</p>
<p>What can, however, entangle the parties is a different rule: once a contract is in place, the employer cannot change a covered term mid-stream without bargaining. But the employer’s flexibility to change non-pay items is among the things the skinny union allows in exchange for more pay. In other words, in a non-union workforce, the employer is typically at liberty to change non-pay items like scheduling and remote work and dress policies. The skinny union’s proposition is not to interfere with such flexibility but remain focused on pay and benefits, and to get paid for the flexibility it is, in effect, “selling” to the employer. To effect this, the union needs to give up that mid-term bargaining right by waiving it in language the Board calls "clear and unmistakable."</p>
<p>The Board reinstated that demanding standard in <em>Endurance Environmental Solutions</em> (December 10, 2024), discarding the looser "contract-coverage" test it had used since 2019. A general "management retains all rights" clause no longer does the job; the clause must name the specific subjects over which the union gives up future bargaining. That specificity requirement — not the duty to bargain — is the real drafting problem the model solves. (And, look, <em>Endurance</em> is a recent decision. Future Boards could make the standard easier to meet.)</p>
<div class="box-break"><aside class="box-technical-note">
  <p class="box-eyebrow">Technical note &mdash; the waiver standard</p>
  <h4 class="box-title">The waiver standard, after Endurance</h4>

  <p class="box-para">To change a covered term mid-contract, an employer ordinarily must bargain first &mdash; unless the union has waived that right in language the Board calls &ldquo;clear and unmistakable.&rdquo;</p>

  <p class="box-para"><a href="https://www.nlrb.gov/news-outreach/news-story/board-returns-to-clear-and-unmistakable-waiver-standard" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><em>Endurance Environmental Solutions</em></a> (Dec. 10, 2024) reinstated that demanding standard, discarding the looser &ldquo;contract-coverage&rdquo; test the Board had used since 2019. A general &ldquo;management retains all rights&rdquo; clause no longer satisfies it; the waiver must name the specific subjects the union gives up.</p>

  <p class="box-caution"><em>Endurance</em> is a recent decision. A future Board could relax the standard again.</p>
</aside></div>
<p>This may seem a circuitous way to reach the result, and it is. As the law stands, there is no recognized path to a union whose representative status is itself limited to pay and benefits; the limitation must be achieved as a bargaining outcome, through the settled tools this section describes. Whether the law should offer a direct path is a fair question, but one worth taking up only if the model earns adoption in its current, lawful form.</p>
<p>There is more than one settled way to address the requirements of an effective waiver. The leanest is the labor bar's standard triad: a management-rights clause, a "zipper" clause closing the contract to mid-term reopening, and an enumerated waiver listing, subject by subject, the non-wage topics the union agrees not to reopen during the term. This is decades-old drafting; it imports no outside document and reaches the result directly.</p>
<p>Another method involves expressly incorporating some or all of an existing employee handbook. This could take the form of partial incorporation, writing only the handbook provisions that touch mandatory subjects (discipline, grievance, discharge standards) into the contract. Or it could take the form of whole-handbook incorporation, which pulls the entire employee handbook in as contractual text. All three produce the identical union — wage-and-benefits-focused, with no grievance apparatus — and differ only in how much of the employer's existing policy becomes frozen contractual text the employer can no longer change unilaterally. That difference is enforcement burden, the very thing the skinny union keeps small.</p>
<p>That is why the triad is the natural default and incorporation the conditional choice, reserved for handbooks that actually contain protections workers value and want frozen. Wholesale incorporation carries a hazard the leaner techniques avoid: if the handbook contains provisions the Board independently regards as unlawful — overbroad confidentiality, conduct, or social-media rules — incorporation can freeze them into the contract, where they could be challenging to fix. Where a handbook is little more than at-will boilerplate, incorporating it freezes an almost empty floor while generating a great deal of drafting ceremony; the triad reaches the same place with less to draft.</p>
<div class="box-break"><aside class="box-technical-note">
  <p class="box-eyebrow">Technical note &mdash; drafting the waiver</p>
  <h4 class="box-title">Three ways to draft the waiver</h4>

  <dl class="box-term-list">
    <dt class="box-term-label">Management-rights clause</dt>
    <dd class="box-para">Affirms the employer retains discretion over the listed subjects.</dd>

    <dt class="box-term-label">Zipper clause</dt>
    <dd class="box-para">Closes the contract to mid-term reopening by either party.</dd>

    <dt class="box-term-label">Enumerated waiver</dt>
    <dd class="box-para">Lists, subject by subject, the non-wage topics the union agrees not to reopen during the term.</dd>
  </dl>

  <p class="box-para">Decades-old drafting. Imports no outside document and reaches the result directly &mdash; the leanest of the available techniques.</p>
</aside></div>
<p>The advantage, if there is one, to handbook incorporation, is in messaging to potential skinny union members. “We are just trying,” an organizer says to her colleagues, “to get us all paid more, but we are aiming to keep the handbook as it is. You know the handbook – it’s, like, fine, right? Let’s just get paid more.”</p>
<p>Just to be clear: the skinny union model does not limit the union's <em>representational</em> scope. The union represents the whole unit and bargains over everything it must; on the non-pay subjects, the bargained outcome is simply to leave the existing arrangement in place. That is a result of bargaining, not an evasion of it. The framing that captures the point is this: the skinny union is not trying to take management's flexibility away; it is making the employer pay fairly for that flexibility. Management keeps its operational discretion (remote-work policy, use of new technologies, restructuring) and the workers convert their collective leverage into the one thing statute cannot supply and individual negotiation cannot match: better compensation. One thing none of the techniques delivers is protection against at-will termination; where the handbook is incorporated, its at-will language comes in as a binding term. The model brings bargaining power to pay without disturbing at-will employment.</p>
<p>A word on a doctrine that sounds like an objection but is not. "Boulwarism" is a word from the <em>General Electric</em> line of cases condemning take-it-or-leave-it bargaining. This is an <em>employer's</em> doctrine. A union that engages in good faith and then agrees to preserve existing terms is the accepting party in an exchange, not the one dictating it. The real task in any of these techniques is not avoiding bad-faith bargaining; it is getting the waiver language specific enough.</p>
<p>Also, it cannot be forgotten at any point that a union has to be the workers' organization, not the company's. Federal law prohibits employer-dominated or employer-assisted labor organizations, the classic “company union,” and the prohibition runs to how the organization is formed and sustained, not to what its bargaining produces. A skinny union that workers organize themselves, fund themselves, and bring to the employer through the ordinary recognition channels is clean. The same structure suggested, staffed, or bankrolled by the employer is not, no matter how attractive the employer finds the model. That is a design constraint, and the organizing kit treats it as one, from formation through the signing of the first contract.</p>
<p>Finally, recognition comes by one of two routes. An employer may recognize the union voluntarily (faster, cheaper, less adversarial, and the route to prefer) or the question goes to a Board election. If the union wins the election, the employer must bargain.</p>
<p>Under the Board's current framework (Cemex, 2023), an employer confronted with a majority-backed demand for recognition cannot simply wait: within roughly two weeks it must either recognize the union or itself petition for an election, and misconduct during the campaign can cost it the election option altogether. Fair warning that this is the most unsettled corner of the law the model touches. The first federal appeals court to review Cemex's remedial half rejected it in March 2026 (Brown-Forman), the Board is expected to revisit the framework, and the law may revert toward the older rule (Linden Lumber, 1974) under which an employer could insist on an election and wait. Either way, absent voluntary recognition, the union can force the issue with an election.</p>
<p>One caution belongs in the open: the “recognition bar” that shields a newly recognized union from challenge for a reasonable period is a Board-made rule that has swung repeatedly with the Board's composition, so prompt bargaining after recognition (and ultimately a signed contract) is the durable protection, not reliance on the bar itself.</p>
<div class="box-break"><aside class="box-technical-note">
  <p class="box-eyebrow">Technical note &mdash; recognition</p>
  <h4 class="box-title">Two paths to recognition</h4>

  <p class="box-para"><span class="box-term-label">Path 1 &mdash; Voluntary recognition</span>The employer recognizes the union directly. Faster, cheaper, less adversarial; the route to prefer.</p>

  <p class="box-para"><span class="box-term-label">Path 2 &mdash; Board election</span>Under the Board&rsquo;s current framework (<em>Cemex</em>, 2023), an employer confronted with a majority-backed demand cannot simply decline and wait &mdash; within roughly two weeks it must recognize the union or itself petition for an election. The Sixth Circuit&rsquo;s <em>Brown-Forman</em> decision (Mar. 2026) rejected only <em>Cemex</em>&rsquo;s bargaining-order remedy, leaving this recognize-or-petition framework intact. The older rule &mdash; <a href="https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/109123/linden-lumber-division-summer-co-v-national-labor-relations-board/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><em>Linden Lumber</em></a> (1974), under which an employer could simply insist on an election and wait &mdash; is what the law may revert to if the Board changes course.</p>

  <p class="box-caution">The &ldquo;recognition bar&rdquo; that shields a newly recognized union from challenge for a reasonable period is a Board-made rule that has swung with the Board&rsquo;s composition. Prompt bargaining after recognition &mdash; and ultimately a signed contract &mdash; is the durable protection, not reliance on the bar.</p>
</aside></div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Economics Notes">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Section IV</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Economics Notes</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <p>Will it work? Not will it work under the law, or will anybody want to try this, but can we actually expect a skinny union to produce gains in pay that justify the hassle of organizing?</p>
<p>Non-union workers face and also accept precarity and a fundamental lack of job security, but also operate in a liquid labor market where capable workers are generally able to find jobs. Traditional unions address this by offering to <em>attack</em> the risk (by bargaining for just cause protection, grievance machinery, layoff procedures, all of which spend down limited bargaining power). Another option would be to <em>price</em> the risk: leave the at-will arrangement and other aspects of employer flexibility in place, while using leverage to extract pay packages that the arrangement warrants. The skinny union’s contention is not that the latter approach is always better, but that it has not been offered at all even though it would be a valuable addition to the menu of options that workers have. It is a pretty clean proposition! If a job is scarier, it should pay more. Do economic theory and applicable data back this up?</p>
<p>We invite labor economists to contribute to these speculations, but, here is how it looks to us:</p>
<p>First, theory and intuition both suggest strongly that there is a premium to be captured for less desirable work. The idea of compensating differentials is old. Adam Smith noticed that disagreeable work commands a premium. Modern forms of this intuition have been elaborated by Rosen’s foundational work through Lavetti’s 2023 survey in the <em>Journal of Economic Perspectives</em>, holding that undesirable job characteristics should be priced into wages: a worker who bears more of a bad thing, insecurity very much included, should be paid more to bear it, all else equal. This does not seem to be a contested corner of the field. If insecurity is a cost the worker carries, the wage is supposed to reflect it.</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
If insecurity is a cost the worker carries, the wage is supposed to reflect it.
</blockquote>
<p>The awkward fact is that the market does not necessarily comply with the intuition here. The empirical record on compensating differentials seems, generously, mixed: the premiums that theory predicts are hard to find and often appear to run the wrong way. Lavetti, surveying the field, is candid that the estimates face persistent credibility problems; Bonhomme and Jolivet titled their study of the matter, accurately, around the pervasive <em>absence</em> of the differentials theory says should be there.</p>
<p>And this is where we pipe up and say: this absence is the argument for the skinny union. A premium that theory says is owed and the market routinely fails to deliver is exactly the gap the skinny union exists to close. The individual worker cannot collect it alone; that is precisely why she is underpaid. And the one institution built to collect it, the traditional union, has historically spent its leverage attacking the risk rather than pricing it. The premium goes unpaid because no one is organized to demand it.</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
A premium that theory says is owed and the market routinely fails to deliver is exactly the gap the skinny union exists to close
</blockquote>
<p>Furthermore, to the extent that new software tools (so-called “artificial intelligence”) are implemented with a view to reducing white-collar work forces, one response might be to double down on the traditional union’s job security goals. And we expect that to emerge. But in this dynamic moment, there is all the more reason for remaining workers to form skinny unions to ensure that the premiums generated by labor saving technology do not redound entirely to senior management and owners. And, because the skinny union is expected to be substantially cheaper to operate than a traditional union, with correspondingly low dues, and because it offers a simpler entry point for collective bargaining, this is the model that is built for the urgency of the moment.</p>
<p>In short, intuition expects there to be a premium to capture by accepting at-will employment and other employer flexibility on non-wage terms, but we also expect that collective action is the method most suited to capturing that premium. At the end of the day, while there are a number of areas worth researching further (some of which are set out below), the desirability and effectiveness of a skinny union model is a reasoned conjecture that will need to be tested in the real world.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Future Research Agenda">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Section V</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Future Research Agenda</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <p>We are convinced that the skinny union is a model worth trying for workers. At the moment, since it does not yet exist, that confidence rests on intuition and experience rather than data. There is a great deal of research that could challenge or strengthen it, though. Here are some of the questions we would most like to see taken up:</p>
<ul>
<li><p><em>The premium itself.</em> The compensating-differentials literature predicts a wage premium for bearing insecurity, yet the empirical record finds that premium weak or missing — Lavetti's 2023 survey is candid about the credibility problems, and Bonhomme and Jolivet built their study around its absence. Is the gap between the premium theory predicts and the one the market delivers real and measurable, and is collective action the instrument that closes it? This is a central testable conjecture of the Skinny Union Project.</p></li>
<li><p><em>What is the premium?</em> To what extent should the premium be viewed as risk that the employee is taking on and seeking fair pay for, on the one hand, or operational flexibility that the employees are selling to the employer, on the other? Are these purely reciprocal framings in theory and practice?</p></li>
<li><p><em>The professional union benchmark</em>. What wage premium do unionized professionals actually earn relative to comparable non-union professionals, once composition is controlled for? A clean estimate — extractable from IPUMS-CPS — is the benchmark the skinny union aims to match at lower operating cost.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Monopsony in professional labor</em>. How much wage-setting power do employers hold over salaried professionals, and how much of it could collective bargaining recover? Matched employer-employee designs (the AKM tradition; Beauregard, Lemieux, Messacar, and Saggio's 2025 NBER work) offer a way to measure this that the older close-election studies do not.</p></li>
<li><p><em>The real cost of the risk being priced and flexibility being sold</em>. The model proposes to price the employer's flexibility rather than attack it. The question is what that flexibility is worth — and the place to look is the gap between what counts as "just cause" under a traditional contract and the lower "performance-related" standard an at-will employer is advised to document to limit its own discrimination-suit exposure. That gap is significant; outright capricious terminations are the visible edge of a much larger zone of discretion a just-cause regime would foreclose. How much is that discretion worth to employers, and how much of its value could collective bargaining convert into pay?</p></li>
<li><p><em>Whether the price of insecurity is falling</em>. White-collar layoffs appear to have grown more common without a matching rise in pay, and labor-saving software may accelerate the trend. Is the implicit premium for insecurity eroding and does that sharpen the case for organizing now?</p></li>
<li><p><em>Where the gains go</em>. Within-firm pay dispersion appears to have widened, labor's share of output has fallen, and a growing stream of compensation accrues to senior management. Whether a wages-and-benefits instrument can redirect any meaningful share of this is genuinely open: the claim is unpersuasive in its generic form, but the question deserves serious empirical attention.</p></li>
<li><p><em>Which gaps are the right targets</em>. Pay gaps come in many cuts — within-firm, between-firm, regional, union versus non-union, and sector comparisons like public versus private employment. Which of these does a skinny union have the realistic leverage to close, and how should the data be framed to find them?</p></li>
<li><p><em>The substitutes objection</em>. If statutory protection keeps expanding, or sectoral bargaining gains ground, is a worker-organized wage instrument still needed? We think so — but the objection deserves a real answer rather than a dismissal.</p></li>
</ul>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="A Note on Right To Work States">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Section VI</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">A Note on Right To Work States</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <p>As noted above, the rising floor in progressive jurisdictions is an ideal setting for skinny unions, but there is also a way in which they could be attractive in right-to-work states.</p>
<p>Right-to-work laws let workers benefit from a union's bargaining without joining or paying dues, which creates an obvious free-rider problem. Traditional unions have been financially wounded by this free-rider problem for decades. As intended, it has made collective bargaining under traditional models especially difficult.</p>
<p>But look at what free-riding actually starves. It starves overhead: staff, offices, the grievance machinery a traditional union carries. A skinny union has almost none of that to begin with. Its dues are lower because its structure is lean by design, not because it is struggling. The economics are fixed-cost coverage: an organization with minimal overhead can stay operational on a thinner dues base, so the free-rider attrition that could be fatal to a full-service local may leave a skinny union bruised but functioning.</p>
<p>That does not make the skinny union immune to free-riding. Fewer dues-paying members still means less bargaining leverage at the table, and a smaller treasury is a smaller treasury regardless of what it was built to fund. But the model's viability in a right-to-work state may not rest on the same foundation as its viability elsewhere. In dense-statutory-protection jurisdictions, the case for a skinny union rests on capturing a wage premium the market fails to deliver on its own. In right-to-work states, the case may rest instead on structural durability: an organization with less overhead to starve is, mechanically, harder to starve. Perhaps more importantly, by establishing an easy, affordable entry into collective bargaining, the skinny union could introduce unionization in jurisdictions where local laws have suppressed organization.</p>
<blockquote class="pull-quote">
In right-to-work states, the case may rest instead on structural durability: an organization with less overhead to starve is, mechanically, harder to starve.
</blockquote>
<p>Like the Skinny Union Project as a whole, this is a hypothesis that would need to be tested in the real world. If valid, this reasoning substantially expands the regions where skinny unions could be viable.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

